# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: multiple-regression
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] In machine learning, **feature selection** is the process of selecting a subset of relevant features (variables, predictors) for use in model construction.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] The central premise when using feature selection is that data sometimes contains features that are *redundant* or *irrelevant*, and can thus be removed without incurring much loss of information.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Redundancy and irrelevance are two distinct notions, since one relevant feature may be redundant in the presence of another relevant feature with which it is strongly correlated.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Feature extraction creates new features from functions of the original features, whereas feature selection finds a subset of the features.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Feature selection techniques are often used in domains where there are many features and comparatively few samples (data points).
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] A feature selection algorithm can be seen as the combination of a search technique for proposing new feature subsets, along with an evaluation measure which scores the different feature subsets.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] The simplest algorithm is to test each possible subset of features finding the one which minimizes the error rate.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] This is an exhaustive search of the space, and is computationally intractable for all but the smallest of feature sets.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] The choice of evaluation metric heavily influences the algorithm, and it is these evaluation metrics which distinguish between the three main categories of feature selection algorithms: wrappers, filters and embedded methods.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] In traditional regression analysis, the most popular form of feature selection is stepwise regression, which is a wrapper technique.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] It is a greedy algorithm that adds the best feature (or deletes the worst feature) at each round.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] The main control issue is deciding when to stop the algorithm.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] In machine learning, this is typically done by cross-validation.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] In statistics, some criteria are optimized.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] This leads to the inherent problem of nesting.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] More robust methods have been explored, such as branch and bound and piecewise linear network.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Subset selection evaluates a subset of features as a group for suitability.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Subset selection algorithms can be broken up into wrappers, filters, and embedded methods.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Wrappers use a search algorithm to search through the space of possible features and evaluate each subset by running a model on the subset.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Wrappers can be computationally expensive and have a risk of over fitting to the model.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Filters are similar to wrappers in the search approach, but instead of evaluating against a model, a simpler filter is evaluated.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Embedded techniques are embedded in, and specific to, a model.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Many popular search approaches use greedy hill climbing, which iteratively evaluates a candidate subset of features, then modifies the subset and evaluates if the new subset is an improvement over the old.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Evaluation of the subsets requires a scoring metric that grades a subset of features.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Exhaustive search is generally impractical, so at some implementor (or operator) defined stopping point, the subset of features with the highest score discovered up to that point is selected as the satisfactory feature subset.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] The stopping criterion varies by algorithm; possible criteria include: a subset score exceeds a threshold, a program's maximum allowed run time has been surpassed, etc.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Alternative search-based techniques are based on targeted projection pursuit which finds low-dimensional projections of the data that score highly: the features that have the largest projections in the lower-dimensional space are then selected.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] These scores are computed between a candidate feature (or set of features) and the desired output category.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] There are, however, true metrics that are a simple function of the mutual information; see here.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] The choice of optimality criteria is difficult as there are multiple objectives in a feature selection task.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Many common criteria incorporate a measure of accuracy, penalised by the number of features selected.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Examples include Akaike information criterion (AIC) and Mallows's *Cp*, which have a penalty of 2 for each added feature.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] AIC is based on information theory, and is effectively derived via the maximum entropy principle.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] A maximum entropy rate criterion may also be used to select the most relevant subset of features.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Filter feature selection is a specific case of a more general paradigm called structure learning.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Feature selection finds the relevant feature set for a specific target variable whereas structure learning finds the relationships between all the variables, usually by expressing these relationships as a graph.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] The most common structure learning algorithms assume the data is generated by a Bayesian Network, and so the structure is a directed graphical model.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] The optimal solution to the filter feature selection problem is the Markov blanket of the target node, and in a Bayesian Network, there is a unique Markov Blanket for each node.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] There are different Feature Selection mechanisms around that utilize mutual information for scoring the different features.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] The simplest approach uses the mutual information as the "derived" score.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] However, there are different approaches, that try to reduce the redundancy between features.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Peng *et al.* proposed a feature selection method that can use either mutual information, correlation, or distance/similarity scores to select features.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] The aim is to penalise a feature's relevancy by its redundancy in the presence of the other selected features.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Suppose that there are n full-set features.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Let *xi* be the set membership indicator function for feature *fi*, so that *xi*=1 indicates presence and *xi*=0 indicates absence of the feature *fi* in the globally optimal feature set.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] The mRMR algorithm is an approximation of the theoretically optimal maximum-dependency feature selection algorithm that maximizes the mutual information between the joint distribution of the selected features and the classification variable.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] As mRMR approximates the combinatorial estimation problem with a series of much smaller problems, each of which only involves two variables, it thus uses pairwise joint probabilities which are more robust.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] In certain situations the algorithm may underestimate the usefulness of features as it has no way to measure interactions between features which can increase relevancy.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] This can lead to poor performance when the features are individually useless, but are useful when combined (a pathological case is found when the class is a parity function of the features).
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Overall the algorithm is more efficient (in terms of the amount of data required) than the theoretically optimal max-dependency selection, yet produces a feature set with little pairwise redundancy.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] mRMR is an instance of a large class of filter methods which trade off between relevancy and redundancy in different ways.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] mRMR is a typical example of an incremental greedy strategy for feature selection: once a feature has been selected, it cannot be deselected at a later stage.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] where $F_{n\times 1}=[I(f_{1};c),\ldots ,I(f_{n};c)]^{T}$ is the vector of feature relevancy assuming there are n features in total, $H_{n\times n}=[I(f_{i};f_{j})]_{i,j=1\ldots n}$ is the matrix of feature pairwise redundancy, and $\mathbf {x} _{n\times 1}$ represents relative feature weights.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] QPFS is solved via quadratic programming.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] It is recently shown that QFPS is biased towards features with smaller entropy, due to its placement of the feature self redundancy term $I(f_{i};f_{i})$ on the diagonal of H.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] An advantage of SPECCMI is that it can be solved simply via finding the dominant eigenvector of Q, thus is very scalable.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] SPECCMI also handles second-order feature interaction.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] In a study of different scores Brown et al. recommended the joint mutual information as a good score for feature selection.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] The score tries to find the feature, that adds the most new information to the already selected features, in order to avoid redundancy.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] The score uses the conditional mutual information and the mutual information to estimate the redundancy between the already selected features ( $f_{j}\in S$ ) and the feature under investigation ( $f_{i}$ ).
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] For high-dimensional and small sample data (e.g., dimensionality > 105 and the number of samples < 103), the Hilbert-Schmidt Independence Criterion Lasso (HSIC Lasso) is useful.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] HSIC always takes a non-negative value, and is zero if and only if two random variables are statistically independent when a universal reproducing kernel such as the Gaussian kernel is used.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] where $\|\cdot \|_{F}$ is the Frobenius norm.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] The optimization problem is a Lasso problem, and thus it can be efficiently solved with a state-of-the-art Lasso solver such as the dual augmented Lagrangian method.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] The correlation feature selection (CFS) measure evaluates subsets of features on the basis of the following hypothesis: "Good feature subsets contain features highly correlated with the classification, yet uncorrelated to each other".
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Here, ${\overline {r_{cf}}}$ is the average value of all feature-classification correlations, and ${\overline {r_{ff}}}$ is the average value of all feature-feature correlations.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] The $r_{cf_{i}}$ and $r_{f_{i}f_{j}}$ variables are referred to as correlations, but are not necessarily Pearson's correlation coefficient or Spearman's ρ.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Hall's dissertation uses neither of these, but uses three different measures of relatedness, minimum description length (MDL), symmetrical uncertainty, and relief.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] The combinatorial problems above are, in fact, mixed 0–1 linear programming problems that can be solved by using branch-and-bound algorithms.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] The features from a decision tree or a tree ensemble are shown to be redundant.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] A recent method called regularized tree can be used for feature subset selection.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Regularized trees penalize using a variable similar to the variables selected at previous tree nodes for splitting the current node.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Regularized trees only need build one tree model (or one tree ensemble model) and thus are computationally efficient.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Regularized trees naturally handle numerical and categorical features, interactions and nonlinearities.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] They are invariant to attribute scales (units) and insensitive to outliers, and thus, require little data preprocessing such as normalization.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Regularized random forest (RRF) is one type of regularized trees.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] The guided RRF is an enhanced RRF which is guided by the importance scores from an ordinary random forest.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] A metaheuristic is a general description of an algorithm dedicated to solve difficult (typically NP-hard problem) optimization problems for which there is no classical solving methods.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Generally, a metaheuristic is a stochastic algorithm tending to reach a global optimum.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] There are many metaheuristics, from a simple local search to a complex global search algorithm.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] The feature selection methods are typically presented in three classes based on how they combine the selection algorithm and the model building.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Filter type methods select variables regardless of the model.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] They are based only on general features like the correlation with the variable to predict.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Filter methods suppress the least interesting variables.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] The other variables will be part of a classification or a regression model used to classify or to predict data.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] These methods are particularly effective in computation time and robust to overfitting.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Filter methods tend to select redundant variables when they do not consider the relationships between variables.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] However, more elaborate features try to minimize this problem by removing variables highly correlated to each other, such as the Fast Correlation Based Filter (FCBF) algorithm.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Wrapper methods evaluate subsets of variables which allows, unlike filter approaches, to detect the possible interactions amongst variables.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Embedded methods have been recently proposed that try to combine the advantages of both previous methods.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] A learning algorithm takes advantage of its own variable selection process and performs feature selection and classification simultaneously, such as the FRMT algorithm.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] This is a survey of the application of feature selection metaheuristics lately used in the literature.
[src:multiple-regression/feature-selection] Some learning algorithms perform feature selection as part of their overall operation.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] In statistics, an **interaction** may arise when considering the relationship among three or more variables, and describes a situation in which the effect of one causal variable on an outcome depends on the state of a second causal variable (that is, when effects of the two causes are not additive).
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Although commonly thought of in terms of causal relationships, the concept of an interaction can also describe non-causal associations (then also called *moderation* or *effect modification*).
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Interactions are often considered in the context of regression analyses or factorial experiments.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] The presence of interactions can have important implications for the interpretation of statistical models.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] If two variables of interest interact, the relationship between each of the interacting variables and a third "dependent variable" depends on the value of the other interacting variable.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] In practice, this makes it more difficult to predict the consequences of changing the value of a variable, particularly if the variables it interacts with are hard to measure or difficult to control.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] An **interaction variable** or **interaction feature** is a variable constructed from an original set of variables to try to represent either all of the interaction present or some part of it.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] In exploratory statistical analyses it is common to use products of original variables as the basis of testing whether interaction is present with the possibility of substituting other more realistic interaction variables at a later stage.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] When there are more than two explanatory variables, several interaction variables are constructed, with pairwise-products representing pairwise-interactions and higher order products representing higher order interactions.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] is an example of a model with an *interaction* between variables *x*1 and *x*2 ("error" refers to the random variable whose value is that by which *Y* differs from the expected value of *Y*; see errors and residuals in statistics).
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Often, models are presented without the interaction term $d(x_{1}\times x_{2})$ , but this confounds the main effect and interaction effect (i.e., without specifying the interaction term, it is possible that any main effect found is actually due to an interaction).
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Moreover, the hierarchical principle rules that if a model includes interaction between variables, it is also necessary to include the main effects, regardless of their own statistical significance.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] A simple setting in which interactions can arise is a two-factor experiment analyzed using Analysis of Variance (ANOVA).
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Suppose we have two binary factors *A* and *B*.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] For example, these factors might indicate whether either of two treatments were administered to a patient, with the treatments applied either singly, or in combination.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] We can then consider the average treatment response (e.g. the symptom levels following treatment) for each patient, as a function of the treatment combination that was administered.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] In this example, there is no interaction between the two treatments — their effects are additive.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] The reason for this is that the difference in mean response between those subjects receiving treatment *A* and those not receiving treatment *A* is −2 regardless of whether treatment *B* is administered (−2 = 4 − 6) or not (−2 = 5 − 7).
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Note that it automatically follows that the difference in mean response between those subjects receiving treatment *B* and those not receiving treatment *B* is the same regardless of whether treatment *A* is administered (7 − 6 = 5 − 4).
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] then there is an interaction between the treatments — their effects are not additive.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Supposing that greater numbers correspond to a better response, in this situation treatment *B* is helpful on average if the subject is not also receiving treatment *A*, but is detrimental on average if given in combination with treatment *A*.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Treatment *A* is helpful on average regardless of whether treatment *B* is also administered, but it is more helpful in both absolute and relative terms if given alone, rather than in combination with treatment *B*.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Similar observations are made for this particular example in the next section.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] In many applications it is useful to distinguish between qualitative and quantitative interactions.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] A quantitative interaction between *A* and *B* is a situation where the magnitude of the effect of *B* depends on the value of *A*, but the direction of the effect of *B* is constant for all *A*.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] A qualitative interaction between *A* and *B* refers to a situation where both the magnitude and direction of each variable's effect can depend on the value of the other variable.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] The table of means on the left, below, shows a quantitative interaction — treatment *A* is beneficial both when *B* is given, and when *B* is not given, but the benefit is greater when *B* is not given (i.e. when *A* is given alone).
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] The table of means on the right shows a qualitative interaction.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] *A* is harmful when *B* is given, but it is beneficial when *B* is not given.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Note that the same interpretation would hold if we consider the benefit of *B* based on whether *A* is given.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] The distinction between qualitative and quantitative interactions depends on the order in which the variables are considered (in contrast, the property of additivity is invariant to the order of the variables).
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] In the following table, if we focus on the effect of treatment *A*, there is a quantitative interaction — giving treatment *A* will improve the outcome on average regardless of whether treatment *B* is or is not already being given (although the benefit is greater if treatment *A* is given alone).
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] In its simplest form, the assumption of treatment unit additivity states that the observed response *y**ij* from experimental unit *i* when receiving treatment *j* can be written as the sum *y**ij* = *y**i* + *t**j*.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] The assumption of unit treatment additivity implies that every treatment has exactly the same additive effect on each experimental unit.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Since any given experimental unit can only undergo one of the treatments, the assumption of unit treatment additivity is a hypothesis that is not directly falsifiable, according to Cox and Kempthorne.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] However, many consequences of treatment-unit additivity can be falsified.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] For a randomized experiment, the assumption of treatment additivity implies that the variance is constant for all treatments.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Therefore, by contraposition, a necessary condition for unit treatment additivity is that the variance is constant.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] The property of unit treatment additivity is not invariant under a change of scale, so statisticians often use transformations to achieve unit treatment additivity.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] If the response variable is expected to follow a parametric family of probability distributions, then the statistician may specify (in the protocol for the experiment or observational study) that the responses be transformed to stabilize the variance.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] In many cases, a statistician may specify that logarithmic transforms be applied to the responses, which are believed to follow a multiplicative model.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] The assumption of unit treatment additivity was enunciated in experimental design by Kempthorne and Cox.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Kempthorne's use of unit treatment additivity and randomization is similar to the design-based analysis of finite population survey sampling.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] In recent years, it has become common to use the terminology of Donald Rubin, which uses counterfactuals.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Suppose we are comparing two groups of people with respect to some attribute *y*.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] For example, the first group might consist of people who are given a standard treatment for a medical condition, with the second group consisting of people who receive a new treatment with unknown effect.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Taking a "counterfactual" perspective, we can consider an individual whose attribute has value *y* if that individual belongs to the first group, and whose attribute has value *τ*(*y*) if the individual belongs to the second group.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] The assumption of "unit treatment additivity" is that *τ*(*y*) = *τ*, that is, the "treatment effect" does not depend on *y*.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Since we cannot observe both *y* and τ(*y*) for a given individual, this is not testable at the individual level.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] However, unit treatment additivity implies that the cumulative distribution functions *F*1 and *F*2 for the two groups satisfy *F*2(*y*) = *F*1(*y − τ*), as long as the assignment of individuals to groups 1 and 2 is independent of all other factors influencing *y* (i.e. there are no confounders).
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Lack of unit treatment additivity can be viewed as a form of interaction between the treatment assignment (e.g. to groups 1 or 2), and the baseline, or untreated value of *y*.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Sometimes the interacting variables are categorical variables rather than real numbers and the study might then be dealt with as an analysis of variance problem.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] For example, members of a population may be classified by religion and by occupation.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] If one wishes to predict a person's height based only on the person's religion and occupation, a simple *additive* model, i.e., a model without interaction, would add to an overall average height an adjustment for a particular religion and another for a particular occupation.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] A model with interaction, unlike an additive model, could add a further adjustment for the "interaction" between that religion and that occupation.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] This example may cause one to suspect that the word *interaction* is something of a misnomer.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Statistically, the presence of an interaction between categorical variables is generally tested using a form of analysis of variance (ANOVA).
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] If one or more of the variables is continuous in nature, however, it would typically be tested using moderated multiple regression.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] This is so-called because a moderator is a variable that affects the strength of a relationship between two other variables.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Genichi Taguchi contended that interactions could be eliminated from a system by appropriate choice of response variable and transformation.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] However George Box and others have argued that this is not the case in general.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Given *n* predictors, the number of terms in a linear model that includes a constant, every predictor, and every possible interaction is ${\tbinom {n}{0}}+{\tbinom {n}{1}}+{\tbinom {n}{2}}+\cdots +{\tbinom {n}{n}}=2^{n}$ .
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Since this quantity grows exponentially, it readily becomes impractically large.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] One method to limit the size of the model is to limit the order of interactions.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] The below table shows the number of terms for each number of predictors and maximum order of interaction.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] where the interaction term $(x_{1}\times x_{2})$ could be formed explicitly by multiplying two (or more) variables, or implicitly using factorial notation in modern statistical packages such as Stata.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] The components *x*1 and *x*2 might be measurements or {0,1} dummy variables in any combination.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Interactions involving a dummy variable multiplied by a measurement variable are termed *slope dummy variables*, because they estimate and test the difference in slopes between groups 0 and 1.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] When measurement variables are employed in interactions, it is often desirable to work with centered versions, where the variable's mean (or some other reasonably central value) is set as zero.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Centering can make the main effects in interaction models more interpretable, as it reduces the multicollinearity between the interaction term and the main effects.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] The coefficient *a* in the equation above, for example, represents the effect of *x*1 when *x*2 equals zero.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Regression approaches to interaction modeling are very general because they can accommodate additional predictors, and many alternative specifications or estimation strategies beyond ordinary least squares.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Robust, quantile, and mixed-effects (multilevel) models are among the possibilities, as is generalized linear modeling encompassing a wide range of categorical, ordered, counted or otherwise limited dependent variables.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] The graph depicts an education*politics interaction, from a probability-weighted logit regression analysis of survey data.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Interaction plots, also called simple-slope plots, show possible interactions among variables.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Consider a study of the body temperature of different species at different air temperatures, in degrees Fahrenheit.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] The interaction plot may use either the air temperature or the species as the x axis.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] The second factor is represented by lines on the interaction plot.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] There is an interaction between the two factors (air temperature and species) in their effect on the response (body temperature), because the effect of the air temperature depends on the species.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] The interaction is indicated on the plot because the lines are not parallel.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] As a second example, consider a clinical trial on the interaction between stroke severity and the efficacy of a drug on patient survival.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] In the interaction plot, the lines for the mild and moderate stroke groups are parallel, indicating that the drug has the same effect in both groups, so there is no interaction.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] The line for the severe stroke group is not parallel to the other lines, indicating that there is an interaction between stroke severity and drug effect on survival.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] The line for the severe stroke group is flat, indicating that, among these patients, there is no difference in survival between the drug and placebo treatments.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] In contrast, the lines for the mild and moderate stroke groups slope down to the right, indicating that, among these patients, the placebo group has lower survival than drug-treated group.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Analysis of variance and regression analysis are used to test for significant interactions.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Is the yield of good cookies affected by the baking temperature and time in the oven?
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] The table shows data for 8 batches of cookies.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] The data show that the yield of good cookies is best when either (i) temperature is high and time in the oven is short, or (ii) temperature is low and time in the oven is long.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] If the cookies are left in the oven for a long time at a high temperature, there are burnt cookies and the yield is low.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] From the graph and the data, it is clear that the lines are not parallel, indicating that there is an interaction.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] This can be tested using analysis of variance (ANOVA).
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] The first ANOVA model will not include the interaction term.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] That is, the first ANOVA model ignores possible interaction.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] The second ANOVA model will include the interaction term.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] That is, the second ANOVA model explicitly performs a hypothesis test for interaction.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] In the ANOVA model that ignores interaction, neither temperature nor time has a significant effect on yield (p=0.91), which is clearly the incorrect conclusion.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] The more appropriate ANOVA model should test for possible interaction.
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] The temperature:time interaction term is significant (p=0.000180).
[src:multiple-regression/interaction-statistics] Based on the interaction test and the interaction plot, it appears that the effect of time on yield depends on temperature and vice versa.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] In statistics, **multicollinearity** or **collinearity** is a situation where the predictors in a regression model are linearly dependent.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] The Gauss–Markov theorem assumes absence of perfect multicollinearity.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] The adverse effect of highly correlated variables is widely known and proven many times.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] To address the high collinearity of a dataset, variance inflation factor can be used to identify the collinearity of the predictor variables.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Perfect multicollinearity refers to a situation where the predictors are linearly dependent (one can be written as an exact linear function of the others).
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] is an *$N\times (k+1)$* matrix, where *N* is the number of observations, *k* is the number of explanatory variables, and *$N\geq k+1$*.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] If there is an exact linear relationship among the independent variables, then at least one of the columns of X is a linear combination of the others, and so the rank of X (and therefore of $X^{\mathsf {T}}X$ ) is less than *$k+1$*, and the matrix $X^{\mathsf {T}}X$ will not be invertible.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Perfect collinearity is typically caused by including redundant variables in a regression.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] For example, a dataset may include variables for income, expenses, and savings.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] However, because income is equal to expenses plus savings by definition, it is incorrect to include all 3 variables in a regression simultaneously.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Similarly, including a dummy variable for every category (e.g., summer, autumn, winter, and spring) as well as an intercept term will result in perfect collinearity.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] This is known as the dummy variable trap.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] The other common cause of perfect collinearity is attempting to use ordinary least squares when working with very wide datasets (those with more variables than observations).
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] These require more advanced data analysis techniques like Bayesian hierarchical modeling to produce meaningful results.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Sometimes, the variables $X_{j}$ are nearly collinear.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] In this case, the matrix $X^{\mathsf {T}}X$ has an inverse, but it is ill-conditioned.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] A computer algorithm may or may not be able to compute an approximate inverse; even if it can, the resulting inverse may have large rounding errors.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] The standard measure of ill-conditioning in a matrix is the condition index.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] This determines if the inversion of the matrix is numerically unstable with finite-precision numbers, indicating the potential sensitivity of the computed inverse to small changes in the original matrix.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] The condition number is computed by finding the maximum singular value divided by the minimum singular value of the design matrix.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] In the context of collinear variables, the variance inflation factor is the condition number for a particular coefficient.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] **Use an orthogonal representation of the data**.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Poorly-written statistical software will sometimes fail to converge to a correct representation when variables are strongly correlated.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] However, it is still possible to rewrite the regression to use only uncorrelated variables by performing a change of basis.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] In addition to causing numerical problems, imperfect collinearity makes precise estimation of variables difficult.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] In other words, highly correlated variables lead to poor estimates and large standard errors.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] As an example, say that we notice Alice wears her boots whenever it is raining and that there are only puddles when it rains.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Then, we cannot tell whether she wears boots to keep the rain from landing on her feet, or to keep her feet dry if she steps in a puddle.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] The problem with trying to identify how much each of the two variables matters is that they are confounded with each other: our observations are explained equally well by either variable, so we do not know which one of them causes the observed correlations.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] If we observe Alice enough times, we will eventually see her on days where there are puddles but not rain (e.g. because the rain stops before she leaves home).
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] This confounding becomes substantially worse when researchers attempt to ignore or suppress it by excluding these variables from the regression (see #Misuse).
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Excluding multicollinear variables from regressions will invalidate causal inference and produce worse estimates by removing important confounders.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Multicollinearity can significantly affect the stability and interpretability of regression models.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] When predictor variables are highly correlated, the variance of the estimated regression coefficients increases, which may lead to large standard errors and unreliable statistical inference.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] As a result, coefficients may appear statistically insignificant even when the overall model has strong explanatory power.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] This issue does not necessarily reduce predictive performance, but it complicates the interpretation of individual predictors.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] There are many ways to prevent multicollinearity from affecting results by planning ahead of time.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] However, these methods all require a researcher to decide on a procedure and analysis *before* data has been collected (see post hoc analysis and Multicollinearity § Misuse).
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Many regression methods are naturally "robust" to multicollinearity and generally perform better than ordinary least squares regression, even when variables are independent.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Regularized regression techniques such as ridge regression, LASSO, elastic net regression, or spike-and-slab regression are less sensitive to including "useless" predictors, a common cause of collinearity.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] These techniques can detect and remove these predictors automatically to avoid problems.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Bayesian hierarchical models (provided by software like BRMS) can perform such regularization automatically, learning informative priors from the data.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Often, problems caused by the use of frequentist estimation are misunderstood or misdiagnosed as being related to multicollinearity.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Researchers are often frustrated not by multicollinearity, but by their inability to incorporate relevant prior information in regressions.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] For example, complaints that coefficients have "wrong signs" or confidence intervals that "include unrealistic values" indicate there is important prior information that is not being incorporated into the model.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] When this is information is available, it should be incorporated into the prior using Bayesian regression techniques.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Stepwise regression (the procedure of excluding "collinear" or "insignificant" variables) is especially vulnerable to multicollinearity, and is one of the few procedures wholly invalidated by it (with any collinearity resulting in heavily biased estimates and invalidated p-values).
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] When conducting experiments where researchers have control over the predictive variables, researchers can often avoid collinearity by choosing an optimal experimental design in consultation with a statistician.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] While the above strategies work in some situations, estimates using advanced techniques may still produce large standard errors.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] In such cases, the correct response to multicollinearity is to "do nothing".
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] The scientific process often involves null or inconclusive results; not every experiment will be "successful" in the sense of decisively confirmation of the researcher's original hypothesis.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Edward Leamer notes that "The solution to the weak evidence problem is more and better data.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Within the confines of the given data set there is nothing that can be done about weak evidence".
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Leamer notes that "bad" regression results that are often misattributed to multicollinearity instead indicate the researcher has chosen an unrealistic prior probability (generally the flat prior used in OLS).
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Damodar Gujarati writes that "we should rightly accept [our data] are sometimes not very informative about parameters of interest".
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Olivier Blanchard quips that "multicollinearity is God's will, not a problem with OLS"; in other words, when working with observational data, researchers cannot "fix" multicollinearity, only accept it.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Variance inflation factors are often misused as criteria in stepwise regression (i.e. for variable inclusion/exclusion), a use that "lacks any logical basis but also is fundamentally misleading as a rule-of-thumb".
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Excluding collinear variables leads to artificially small estimates for standard errors, but does not reduce the true (not estimated) standard errors for regression coefficients.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Excluding variables with a high variance inflation factor also invalidates the calculated standard errors and p-values, by turning the results of the regression into a post hoc analysis.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Because collinearity leads to large standard errors and p-values, which can make publishing articles more difficult, some researchers will try to suppress inconvenient data by removing strongly-correlated variables from their regression.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] This procedure falls into the broader categories of p-hacking, data dredging, and post hoc analysis.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Dropping (useful) collinear predictors will generally worsen the accuracy of the model and coefficient estimates.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] Similarly, trying many different models or estimation procedures (e.g. ordinary least squares, ridge regression, etc.) until finding one that can "deal with" the collinearity creates a forking paths problem.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] P-values and confidence intervals derived from post hoc analyses are invalidated by ignoring the uncertainty in the model selection procedure.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] It is reasonable to exclude unimportant predictors if they are known ahead of time to have little or no effect on the outcome; for example, local cheese production should not be used to predict the height of skyscrapers.
[src:multiple-regression/multicollinearity] However, this must be done when first specifying the model, prior to observing any data, and potentially-informative variables should always be included.
[src:multiple-regression/multiple-correlation] In statistics, the **coefficient of multiple correlation** is a measure of how well a given variable can be predicted using a linear function of a set of other variables.
[src:multiple-regression/multiple-correlation] It is the correlation between the variable's values and the best predictions that can be computed linearly from the predictive variables.
[src:multiple-regression/multiple-correlation] The coefficient of multiple correlation takes values between 0 and 1.
[src:multiple-regression/multiple-correlation] The coefficient of multiple correlation, denoted *R*, is a scalar that is defined as the Pearson correlation coefficient between the predicted and the actual values of the dependent variable in a linear regression model that includes an intercept.
[src:multiple-regression/multiple-correlation] If all the predictor variables are uncorrelated, the matrix $R_{xx}$ is the identity matrix and $R^{2}$ simply equals $\mathbf {c} ^{\top }\,\mathbf {c}$ , the sum of the squared correlations with the dependent variable.
[src:multiple-regression/multiple-correlation] If the predictor variables are correlated among themselves, the inverse of the correlation matrix $R_{xx}$ accounts for this.
[src:multiple-regression/multiple-correlation] The squared coefficient of multiple correlation can also be computed as the fraction of variance of the dependent variable that is explained by the independent variables, which in turn is 1 minus the unexplained fraction.
[src:multiple-regression/multiple-correlation] The unexplained fraction can be computed as the sum of squares of residuals—that is, the sum of the squares of the prediction errors—divided by the sum of squares of deviations of the values of the dependent variable from its expected value.
[src:multiple-regression/multiple-correlation] With more than two variables being related to each other, the value of the coefficient of multiple correlation depends on the choice of dependent variable: a regression of y on x and z will in general have a different R than will a regression of z on x and y .
[src:multiple-regression/multiple-correlation] For example, suppose that in a particular sample the variable z is uncorrelated with both x and y , while x and y are linearly related to each other.
[src:multiple-regression/multiple-correlation] Then a regression of z on y and x will yield an R of zero, while a regression of y on x and z will yield a strictly positive R .
[src:multiple-regression/multiple-correlation] This follows since the correlation of y with its best predictor based on x and z is in all cases at least as large as the correlation of y with its best predictor based on x alone, and in this case with z providing no explanatory power it will be exactly as large.
[src:multiple-regression/partial-regression-plot] In applied statistics, a **partial regression plot** attempts to show the effect of adding another variable to a model that already has one or more independent variables.
[src:multiple-regression/partial-regression-plot] Partial regression plots are also referred to as **added variable plots**, **adjusted variable plots**, and **individual coefficient plots**.
[src:multiple-regression/partial-regression-plot] When performing a linear regression with a single independent variable, a scatter plot of the response variable against the independent variable provides a good indication of the nature of the relationship.
[src:multiple-regression/partial-regression-plot] If there is more than one independent variable, things become more complicated since independent variables might be (negatively or positively) correlated.
[src:multiple-regression/partial-regression-plot] Although it can still be useful to generate scatter plots of the response variable against each of the independent variables, this does not take into account the effect of the other independent variables in the model.
[src:multiple-regression/partial-regression-plot] For example, due to omitted variable bias, a simple scatter plot might display a strong positive slope between $Y_{i}$ and $X_{i}$ , even when the true multivariate coefficient $\beta _{i}$ in the full model is negative.
[src:multiple-regression/partial-regression-plot] Plotting the residuals from (1) against the residuals from (2).
[src:multiple-regression/partial-regression-plot] against the remaining independent variables.
[src:multiple-regression/partial-regression-plot] The residuals from the least squares linear fit to this plot are identical to the residuals from the least squares fit of the original model (Y against all the independent variables including Xi).
[src:multiple-regression/partial-regression-plot] The influences of individual data values on the estimation of a coefficient are easy to see in this plot.
[src:multiple-regression/partial-regression-plot] It is easy to see many kinds of failures of the model or violations of the underlying assumptions (nonlinearity, heteroscedasticity, unusual patterns). .
[src:multiple-regression/partial-regression-plot] Partial regression plots are related to, but distinct from, partial residual plots.
[src:multiple-regression/partial-regression-plot] Partial regression plots are most commonly used to identify data points with high leverage and influential data points that might not have high leverage.
[src:multiple-regression/partial-regression-plot] Partial residual plots are most commonly used to identify the nature of the relationship between *Y* and *X*i (given the effect of the other independent variables in the model).
[src:multiple-regression/partial-regression-plot] Note that since the simple correlation between the two sets of residuals plotted is equal to the partial correlation between the response variable and *X*i, partial regression plots will show the correct strength of the linear relationship between the response variable and *X*i.
[src:multiple-regression/partial-regression-plot] This is not true for partial residual plots.
[src:multiple-regression/partial-regression-plot] On the other hand, for the partial regression plot, the x-axis is not *X*i.
[src:multiple-regression/partial-regression-plot] This limits its usefulness in determining the need for a transformation (which is the primary purpose of the partial residual plot).
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] In statistics, **stepwise regression** is a method of fitting regression models in which the choice of predictive variables is carried out by an automatic procedure.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] In each step, a variable is considered for addition to or subtraction from the set of explanatory variables based on some prespecified criterion.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] Usually, this takes the form of a forward, backward, or combined sequence of *F*-tests or *t*-tests.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] A widely used algorithm was first proposed by Efroymson (1960).
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] This is an automatic procedure for statistical *model selection* in cases where there is a large number of potential explanatory variables, and no underlying theory on which to base the model selection.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] The procedure is used primarily in regression analysis, though the basic approach is applicable in many forms of model selection.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] This is a variation on forward selection.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] At each stage in the process, after a new variable is added, a test is made to check if some variables can be deleted without appreciably increasing the residual sum of squares (RSS).
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] The procedure terminates when the measure is (locally) maximized, or when the available improvement falls below some critical value.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] One of the main issues with stepwise regression is that it searches a large space of possible models.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] Hence it is prone to overfitting the data.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] In other words, stepwise regression will often fit much better in sample than it does on new out-of-sample data.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] Extreme cases have been noted where models have achieved statistical significance working on random numbers.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] This problem can be mitigated if the criterion for adding (or deleting) a variable is stiff enough.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] The key line in the sand is at what can be thought of as the Bonferroni point: namely how significant the best spurious variable should be based on chance alone.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] On a *t*-statistic scale, this occurs at about ${\sqrt {2\log p}}$ , where *p* is the number of predictors.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] Unfortunately, this means that many variables which actually carry signal will not be included.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] This fence turns out to be the right trade-off between over-fitting and missing signal.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] If we look at the risk of different cutoffs, then using this bound will be within a $2\log p$ factor of the best possible risk.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] Any other cutoff will end up having a larger such risk inflation.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] A way to test for errors in models created by step-wise regression, is to not rely on the model's *F*-statistic, significance, or multiple R, but instead assess the model against a set of data that was not used to create the model.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] This is often done by building a model based on a sample of the dataset available (e.g., 70%) – the “training set” – and use the remainder of the dataset (e.g., 30%) as a validation set to assess the accuracy of the model.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] Accuracy is then often measured as the actual standard error (SE), MAPE (Mean absolute percentage error), or mean error between the predicted value and the actual value in the hold-out sample.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] This method is particularly valuable when data are collected in different settings (e.g., different times, social vs. solitary situations) or when models are assumed to be generalizable.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] Stepwise regression procedures are used in data mining, but are controversial.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] Several points of criticism have been made.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] Such criticisms, based upon limitations of the relationship between a model and procedure and data set used to fit it, are usually addressed by verifying the model on an independent data set, as in the PRESS procedure.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] Critics regard the procedure as a paradigmatic example of data dredging, intense computation often being an inadequate substitute for subject area expertise.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] Additionally, the results of stepwise regression are often used incorrectly without adjusting them for the occurrence of model selection.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] Especially the practice of fitting the final selected model as if no model selection had taken place and reporting of estimates and confidence intervals as if least-squares theory were valid for them, has been described as a scandal.
[src:multiple-regression/stepwise-regression] Widespread incorrect usage and the availability of alternatives such as ensemble learning, leaving all variables in the model, or using expert judgement to identify relevant variables have led to calls to totally avoid stepwise model selection.
[src:multiple-regression/variance-inflation-factor] In statistics, the **variance inflation factor** (**VIF**) is the ratio (quotient) of the variance of a parameter estimate when fitting a full model that includes other parameters to the variance of the parameter estimate if the model is fit with only the parameter on its own.
[src:multiple-regression/variance-inflation-factor] The VIF provides an index that measures how much the variance (the square of the estimate's standard deviation) of an estimated regression coefficient is increased because of collinearity.
[src:multiple-regression/variance-inflation-factor] Cuthbert Daniel claims to have invented the concept behind the variance inflation factor, but did not come up with the name.
[src:multiple-regression/variance-inflation-factor] where *R**j*2 is the multiple *R*2 for the regression of *X**j* on the other covariates (a regression that does not involve the response variable *Y*) and ${\hat {\beta }}_{j}$ are the coefficient estimates, id est, the estimates of ${\beta }_{j}$ .
[src:multiple-regression/variance-inflation-factor] The remaining term, 1 / (1 − *R**j*2) is the VIF.
[src:multiple-regression/variance-inflation-factor] It reflects all other factors that influence the uncertainty in the coefficient estimates.
[src:multiple-regression/variance-inflation-factor] The VIF equals 1 when the vector *X**j* is orthogonal to each column of the design matrix for the regression of *X**j* on the other covariates.
[src:multiple-regression/variance-inflation-factor] By contrast, the VIF is greater than 1 when the vector *X**j* is not orthogonal to all columns of the design matrix for the regression of *X**j* on the other covariates.
[src:multiple-regression/variance-inflation-factor] Finally, note that the VIF is invariant to the scaling of the variables (that is, we could scale each variable *X**j* by a constant *c**j* without changing the VIF).
[src:multiple-regression/variance-inflation-factor] Here ${\hat {\beta }}_{*j}$ is the coefficient of regression of dependent variable $X_{j}$ over covariate $X_{-j}$ . $\mathrm {RSS} _{j}$ is the corresponding residual sum of squares.
[src:multiple-regression/variance-inflation-factor] First we run an ordinary least square regression that has *X**i* as a function of all the other explanatory variables in the first equation.
[src:multiple-regression/variance-inflation-factor] where $\alpha _{0}$ is a constant and $\varepsilon$ is the error term.
[src:multiple-regression/variance-inflation-factor] where *R*2*i* is the coefficient of determination of the regression equation in step one, with $X_{i}$ on the left hand side, and all other predictor variables (all the other X variables) on the right hand side.
[src:multiple-regression/variance-inflation-factor] Analyze the magnitude of multicollinearity by considering the size of the $\operatorname {VIF} ({\hat {\alpha }}_{i})$ .
[src:multiple-regression/variance-inflation-factor] A rule of thumb is that if $\operatorname {VIF} ({\hat {\alpha }}_{i})>10$ then multicollinearity is high (a cutoff of 5 is also commonly used).
[src:multiple-regression/variance-inflation-factor] However, there is no value of VIF greater than 1 in which the variance of the slopes of predictors isn't inflated.
[src:multiple-regression/variance-inflation-factor] As a result, including two or more variables in a multiple regression that are not orthogonal (i.e. have correlation = 0), will alter each other's slope, SE of the slope, and P-value, because there is shared variance between the predictors that can't be uniquely attributed to any one of them.
[src:multiple-regression/variance-inflation-factor] Some software instead calculates the tolerance which is just the reciprocal of the VIF.
[src:multiple-regression/variance-inflation-factor] The choice of which to use is a matter of personal preference.
[src:multiple-regression/variance-inflation-factor] The square root of the variance inflation factor indicates how much larger the standard error increases compared to if that variable had 0 correlation to other predictor variables in the model.
